sections.technical:
All faculty shall commit to equitable and inclusive teaching practices that support the learning and belonging of all students. Faculty shall:

(a) Create classroom environments that reflect the diversity of identities and experiences in the school and world;

(b) Incorporate curriculum materials and examples that represent varied perspectives, voices, experiences, and contributions of people from different backgrounds and identities;

(c) Use teaching methods and assessment practices that recognize and affirm students' different learning styles, prior knowledge, and ways of knowing;

(d) Actively monitor classroom participation and contribution to ensure that all students have opportunities to speak, ask questions, and engage;

(e) Demonstrate awareness of and accountability for their own implicit biases and the impact of their biases on student learning and belonging;

(f) Build relationships with students that demonstrate genuine care and recognition of students' full identities and contexts;

(g) Maintain high expectations for all students and provide appropriate supports to ensure equitable access to rigorous learning.

sections.standard:
All faculty shall commit to fair and welcoming teaching practices that support the learning and belonging of all students. Faculty shall:

(a) Create classroom environments that reflect the varied identities and experiences in the school and world;

(b) Incorporate curriculum materials and examples that represent varied perspectives, voices, experiences, and contributions of people from different backgrounds and identities;

(c) Use teaching methods and assessment practices that recognize and affirm students' different learning styles, prior knowledge, and ways of knowing;

(d) Actively monitor classroom participation and contribution to ensure that all students have opportunities to speak, ask questions, and engage;

(e) Demonstrate awareness of and accountability for their own unexamined assumptions and the impact on student learning and belonging;

(f) Build relationships with students that demonstrate genuine care and recognition of students' full identities and contexts;

(g) Maintain high expectations for all students and provide appropriate supports to ensure fair access to rigorous learning.

sections.simplePlain:
Teachers should teach in ways that are fair to all students and help everyone feel they belong. This means:

(a) Making classrooms reflect the different kinds of people in the school and the world;

(b) Using books and examples that show different perspectives and come from people with different backgrounds;

(c) Teaching and testing in ways that recognize that students learn differently;

(d) Making sure all students get to participate and speak in class;

(e) Thinking about their own biases and how those might affect how they teach different students;

(f) Actually caring about and getting to know students as whole people;

(g) Believing all students can do the work and giving them help they need to succeed.

sections.technical:
All vendor selection processes shall incorporate assessment of vendors' commitment to diversity, equity, and inclusive practices. The school shall use a comprehensive DEI rubric that evaluates vendors on a 4-point scale ("Don't Know" to "Practice and Evaluation") across 16+ criteria including:

(a) Minority Ownership: Percentage of the business owned by people from underrepresented communities;

(b) Equitable Hiring: Evidence of active recruitment, hiring, and advancement of employees from underrepresented backgrounds;

(c) Living Wage: Commitment to paying all employees a living wage and providing benefits;

(d) Healthcare Access: Provision of healthcare benefits to all full-time and part-time employees;

(e) Disability Accommodations: Workplace accommodations and accessibility for employees and customers with disabilities;

(f) Multilingual Services: Availability of services, materials, and communication in multiple languages;

(g) Affinity Groups: Employee affinity groups or employee resource groups supporting employees from marginalized communities;

(h) Green Certification: Environmental certifications or demonstrated commitment to sustainable practices;

(i) Sustainability Practices: Waste reduction, renewable energy, sustainable sourcing, or other environmental initiatives;

(j) B Corp Certification: B Corp or similar third-party certification for social and environmental responsibility;

(k) Body Size Inclusion: Inclusive sizing and representation in products or services;

(l) Immigrant Opportunity: Welcoming and supporting immigrant employees and customers;

(m) Age Inclusion: Representation and inclusion of workers and customers across age ranges;

(n) Religion Accommodation: Accommodations for religious practices, dietary needs, and observances;

(o) Educational Access: Programs supporting educational advancement for employees or community members;

(p) Direct DEI Programming: Vendor's own diversity and inclusion initiatives or community programming.

Vendors shall be scored on each criterion and overall performance shall weigh into vendor selection decisions.

sections.standard:
All vendor selection processes shall incorporate assessment of vendors' commitment to fair practices and welcoming business culture. The school shall use a comprehensive rubric that evaluates vendors on a 4-point scale ("Don't Know" to "Practice and Evaluation") across 16+ criteria including:

(a) Diverse Ownership: Percentage of the business owned by people from varied backgrounds;

(b) Fair Hiring: Evidence of active recruitment, hiring, and advancement of employees from varied backgrounds;

(c) Fair Wages: Commitment to paying all employees fair wages and providing benefits;

(d) Healthcare Access: Provision of healthcare benefits to all full-time and part-time employees;

(e) Accessibility: Workplace accommodations and accessibility for employees and customers with varying needs;

(f) Multilingual Services: Availability of services, materials, and communication in multiple languages;

(g) Employee Support Groups: Employee resource groups supporting employees from historically excluded communities;

(h) Environmental Practices: Environmental certifications or demonstrated commitment to responsible practices;

(i) Sustainability Practices: Waste reduction, renewable energy, responsible sourcing, or other environmental initiatives;

(j) Ethical Certifications: Third-party certification for social and environmental responsibility;

(k) Inclusive Products: Inclusive sizing and representation in products or services;

(l) Immigrant Opportunity: Welcoming and supporting immigrant employees and customers;

(m) Multi-Generational: Representation and inclusion of workers and customers across age ranges;

(n) Religious Accommodation: Accommodations for religious practices, dietary needs, and observances;

(o) Educational Access: Programs supporting educational advancement for employees or community members;

(p) Community Programming: Vendor's own community initiatives or community programming.

Vendors shall be scored on each criterion and overall performance shall weigh into vendor selection decisions.

sections.simplePlain:
When the school picks vendors to buy from, it looks at whether those companies treat people fairly and are welcoming to everyone. The school uses a scoring system to check how vendors do on things like:

(a) Do people from different backgrounds own part of the company;

(b) Do they actively hire and promote people from different backgrounds;

(c) Do they pay fair wages and provide benefits;

(d) Do they give healthcare to employees;

(e) Do they make accommodations for people with disabilities;

(f) Do they offer services in different languages;

(g) Do they have groups that support employees from underrepresented communities;

(h) Do they have environmental certifications;

(i) Do they use sustainable practices;

(j) Do they have certifications showing they're socially responsible;

(k) Do their products come in different sizes and show different kinds of people;

(l) Do they welcome and support immigrants;

(m) Do they include people of different ages;

(n) Do they respect religious practices and dietary needs;

(o) Do they help people get educated;

(p) Do they do community programs.

These scores help the school decide which companies to buy from.

The school picks food vendors that offer fair and inclusive food choices. The school thinks about things like:

(a) Do they serve different kinds of food that reflect students' cultures;

(b) Can students on financial aid afford to eat;

(c) Do they treat workers fairly and use organic food when possible;

(d) Is the food healthy for teenagers;

(e) Are products and marketing welcoming to all genders;

(f) Do they include options for different family structures;

(g) Are there options for religious dietary rules and restrictions;

(h) Do they handle allergies;

(i) Are portion sizes welcoming to people of different body sizes and not make anyone feel bad;

(j) Are menus in different languages;

(k) Is the food produced responsibly for the environment;

(l) Are there foods from different countries represented.

When the school picks food vendors, it includes these fairness standards in the decision.
